solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item Angular momentum is conserved, but his moment of inertia increases, so his angular velocity decreases. 
        \item The factor of change is $0.9/0.6=1.5$ times greater.
    \end{anum}

\begin{anum}
        \item Note that the angular velocity, in radians per second, is $3\cdot 2\pi$. We have $$L=I\omega=\frac 12 MR^2\omega=\frac 12 \cdot 48\cdot 0.15^2\cdot 3\cdot 2\pi =10.18\, \unit{kg \cdot m^2/s}$$
        \item Using $\tau = \Delta L/\Delta t$, we have $\tau=10.18/4=2.55\, \unit{N\cdot m}$.
